That’s it.

Most candidates fail because they sound like documentation.

Best Interview Flow (2–3 Minutes)

Say this naturally:

=====================================

“JWT is used for stateless authentication.

In traditional session authentication, server stores session data in memory or database.
But in microservices or distributed systems, maintaining sessions across multiple servers becomes difficult.

So we use JWT where authentication data is stored inside a signed token instead of server session.”

==========================
Then explain flow.
====================

JWT Flow (Main Part)

“First user sends login request with email and password.

Spring Security validates credentials using AuthenticationManager and UserDetailsService.

If credentials are correct, server generates JWT token containing claims like userId and role.

Then token is sent back to client.

For every API request, client sends token in Authorization header using Bearer token.

A JWT filter, usually OncePerRequestFilter, intercepts request, validates token signature and expiry.

If token is valid, authentication is stored inside SecurityContextHolder and request becomes authenticated.”

===============================
Then mention security.
===============================

Security Part

“JWT payload is only encoded, not encrypted, so sensitive data should never be stored inside token.

In production we use:

short expiry
HTTPS
HttpOnly cookies
refresh token mechanism”
=======================
Then mention real-world usage.
============================

Microservice Usage

“In microservices architecture, JWT is useful because all services can validate token independently without maintaining shared sessions.”
=========================
Then stop.

Do not keep talking unnecessarily.

If Interviewer Asks “Did You Implement It?”

Say this:

“Yes, I implemented JWT authentication using Spring Security.

I created:

JwtService for token generation and validation
OncePerRequestFilter for intercepting requests
Security configuration for protected APIs
Refresh token flow for token renewal

I also handled role-based authorization using roles inside JWT claims.”
=========================================
IMPORTANT

Avoid beginner mistakes like:

❌ “JWT is more secure than session”

Wrong.

JWT is not automatically more secure.

Correct answer:

“JWT improves scalability and statelessness.”

❌ “JWT payload is encrypted”

Wrong.

It is Base64 encoded.

Huge difference.

❌ “JWT stores password”

Disaster answer.

Never say that.

If They Ask “Why Bearer?”

Say:

“Bearer means whoever possesses the token can access APIs, so token must be protected properly using HTTPS and secure storage.”

If They Ask “Why Refresh Token?”

Say:

“Access token expiry is kept short for security.
Refresh token helps generate new access token without forcing user to login repeatedly.”

